{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651604"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:26:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:26:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18481"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18481"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.08,0.19,0.36,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11210"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80415"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11210"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65695"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7139"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7198"},{"type":"tags","id":"7497"},{"type":"tags","id":"7500"},{"type":"tags","id":"8560"},{"type":"tags","id":"10455"},{"type":"tags","id":"10456"},{"type":"tags","id":"10464"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26260"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80415"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cochlear nerve is a component of the vestibulocochlear nerve (cranial nerve VIII) that transmits auditory information from the inner ear to the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the anatomical course of the cochlear nerve?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Originates from hair cells in the organ of Corti","Synapses in the geniculate ganglion","Connects vestibular organs to cochlear nuclei","Projects from spiral ganglion to cochlear nuclei","Travels directly from cochlea to inferior colliculus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProjects from spiral ganglion to cochlear nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the anatomical course of the cochlear nerve (image). The bipolar neurons of the spiral ganglion receive input from inner hair cells in the organ of Corti and send their central processes to synapse in the dorsal and ventral cochlear nuclei of the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOriginates from hair cells in the organ of Corti\u003C/strong\u003E - While hair cells provide input, the nerve fibres originate from spiral ganglion neurons\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynapses in the geniculate ganglion\u003C/strong\u003E - The geniculate ganglion contains cell bodies of the facial nerve (cranial nerve VII), not the cochlear nerve\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnects vestibular organs to cochlear nuclei\u003C/strong\u003E - Vestibular organs are innervated by the vestibular portion of cranial nerve VIII, not the cochlear portion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETravels directly from cochlea to inferior colliculus\u003C/strong\u003E - The pathway to the inferior colliculus includes obligatory synapses in the cochlear nuclei and superior olive\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cochlear nerve carries tonotopically organised auditory information, maintaining frequency specificity from the cochlea to the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The cochlear nerve carries auditory information from the organ of Corti in the cochlea to the cochlear nuclei in the brainstem.","The cell bodies of cochlear nerve neurons are located in the spiral ganglion within the modiolus of the cochlea.","The cochlear nerve enters the brainstem at the cerebellopontine angle alongside the vestibular nerve as cranial nerve VIII."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cAnatomy of Human Ear with Cochlear Frequency Mapping\u201d by Inductiveload is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 2.5 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.5). \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Anatomy_of_Human_Ear_with_Cochlear_Frequency_Mapping.svg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65695"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18481"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21392"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21392"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9Mrp0e0ohd3Pnib6vls2GKn3ppyai1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9Mrp0e0ohd3Pnib6vls2GKn3ppyai1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":493}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65695"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T16:48:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T16:51:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11210"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80415"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes